WEBVTT

00:09.020 --> 00:13.020
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.660 --> 00:33.960
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.780 --> 00:38.280
And here are your hosts.

00:42.560 --> 00:44.460
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon.

00:44.980 --> 00:47.180
James Gunn approaches science fiction from many angles.

00:47.660 --> 00:51.840
He writes it, he teaches it, and he's published important historical and critical material

00:51.840 --> 00:52.560
in science fiction.

00:53.080 --> 00:57.760
Some of Gunn's better known novels include the Joymakers, the Immortals, the Listeners,

00:57.920 --> 00:58.640
and the Dreamers.

00:59.080 --> 01:03.100
The Immortals was the basis for the television show of a few years back, The Immortal.

01:03.820 --> 01:07.480
Gunn's critical work, in addition to numerous essays, consists of two major publications,

01:08.260 --> 01:12.840
Alternate Worlds, a 1975 history of science fiction, and The Road to Science Fiction,

01:13.060 --> 01:16.860
a four-volume anthology that includes Gunn's essays on the definition of science fiction

01:16.860 --> 01:18.020
and its historical development.

01:18.320 --> 01:22.160
Gunn's criticism is valuable because it not only comes from someone who knows the field,

01:22.280 --> 01:25.880
but also because Gunn is a scholar and professor at a major university.

01:26.260 --> 01:29.200
He brings the insight of a professional academic to the field.

01:29.550 --> 01:33.200
We talked with Gunn about how he divides himself between being both a writer and a teacher.

01:33.780 --> 01:36.380
We asked him if he'd ever considered writing as a full-time career.

01:36.980 --> 01:43.560
I did, as a matter of fact, write full-time for a period of a little more than three years,

01:43.780 --> 01:56.520
a year, in 1948-49, and I went back to school then and got a master's degree, but I continued

01:56.520 --> 02:05.280
to write, and then after I'd worked for this paperback publisher, after I got my master's

02:05.280 --> 02:10.280
degree, worked for a paperback publisher for a year and a half, I found out that I'd sold

02:10.280 --> 02:13.860
four stories that I hadn't known about and decided to go back to full-time writing.

02:14.580 --> 02:26.500
So I did write full-time from the fall of 1942 until the late summer of 1948.

02:26.520 --> 02:34.760
I did write a book in 1955, and really much of the groundwork for the later books that

02:34.760 --> 02:41.640
I published and the success that I had, I think, especially it was, was based upon that

02:42.300 --> 02:47.440
freelance period. I didn't make a lot of money at it, you know, below the poverty level,

02:47.820 --> 02:56.500
but my needs were fairly simple at that time, and what it later paid off in the late 1950s

02:56.520 --> 03:01.880
was, in the sense that the stories that I wrote appeared in books, and some of them

03:01.880 --> 03:03.760
even were made in the movies and all that sort of thing.

03:04.700 --> 03:06.980
Gunn explains how I became involved in teaching.

03:07.840 --> 03:15.960
It was after 1955, or in the fall of 1955, after my wife and I had moved back to Lawrence,

03:16.100 --> 03:23.640
Kansas, simply as a place to live, that I got involved almost by accident with teaching

03:23.640 --> 03:28.920
at the university, from which I'd gotten my two degrees, the University of Kansas, and

03:29.350 --> 03:34.760
became involved with other aspects of the university, edited the alumni magazine for

03:34.760 --> 03:41.440
three years, and then became director of public relations for the university for twelve years,

03:41.660 --> 03:46.700
before returning to full-time teaching and writing in 1970.

03:47.540 --> 03:49.900
Gunn had always intended to write science fiction criticism.

03:50.780 --> 03:59.540
But looking back upon it, I know, I think right from the beginning, I had the feeling

03:59.540 --> 04:07.800
that I wanted to do criticism in the area. My first ten stories, for instance, were

04:07.800 --> 04:19.800
published under a pseudonym of Edwin James, using, I began to use my own name with the

04:19.800 --> 04:26.220
reason I can remember now for doing that, was the fact that I thought I would write

04:26.220 --> 04:32.860
criticism about science fiction, and I wanted to save my real name for that. But after ten

04:32.860 --> 04:39.400
stories, I decided that was foolish, and I ought to use my real name for everything.

04:40.780 --> 04:48.580
But looking back upon it, I think the academic interest was there right from the beginning.

04:49.360 --> 04:53.980
Beginning next time, we'll talk with James Gunn about his writing, both the stories and

04:53.980 --> 04:54.580
the criticism.

