06:31.140 --> 06:36.300
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Anne. James Gunn, author, critic and teacher of science fiction,

06:36.660 --> 06:40.920
has written some valuable books on the definition and historical development of science fiction.

06:41.260 --> 06:45.400
He's examining some big questions in this work, things like what is science fiction,

06:45.740 --> 06:48.520
what makes it different from other literature, and where it comes from.

06:48.640 --> 06:53.180
And since Gunn is a professor at the University of Kansas, besides being a long time author

06:53.180 --> 06:57.640
of science fiction, he combines a scholar's objectivity and a creator's understanding

06:57.640 --> 06:59.080
in answering these questions.

06:59.660 --> 07:04.820
Alternate Worlds, published in 1976, is his first major critical work. Gunn explains its

07:04.820 --> 07:05.140
origin.

07:06.060 --> 07:12.520
I had, when I first went back to full-time teaching, had been asked if I would teach

07:12.520 --> 07:17.920
a science fiction course, which is different from the experience at most universities,

07:17.920 --> 07:27.340
where there is some resistance to the notion of doing that. And I accepted because I had

07:27.340 --> 07:32.360
the feeling that there wasn't a good history of science fiction, and that this course would

07:32.360 --> 07:44.220
give me the incentive to write it. So I sat down and wrote very fast, and ended up with

07:45.160 --> 07:57.140
13 chapters representing about 13 lectures for the 14-week semester. And these chapters

07:57.340 --> 08:05.240
or these lectures became the 13 chapters in a book of mine, which appeared in about,

08:05.520 --> 08:14.240
I guess, 75, after some delays, as Alternate Worlds, the illustrated history of science

08:14.240 --> 08:20.580
fiction. But as it won consequence of its publication, I got a call one day from an

08:20.580 --> 08:27.760
editor at New American Library who was admiring it and asked me if I'd like to do a book

08:27.760 --> 08:39.220
for them. And I knew also that I really felt the need for anthologies which covered more

08:40.020 --> 08:49.260
than the brief span of the 20s to the 60s, which most anthologies did, and there really

08:49.260 --> 08:54.520
wasn't much in the 20s or 30s most of it, appeared, covered the period of the 40s and

08:54.520 --> 09:04.400
50s. So I said yes, and I sent them a proposal for the first volume of the Road Science Fiction.

09:04.540 --> 09:13.360
At that time, all we knew that there would be would be one volume which covered the period

09:13.360 --> 09:22.940
from the earliest prehistory of literature, not to mention science fiction, up to 1900

09:23.720 --> 09:32.560
and the H.G. Wells' early stories and novels. The volume used a unique and valuable approach

09:32.560 --> 09:37.100
to science fiction criticism. It was an anthology of stories, but each story was accompanied

09:37.100 --> 09:41.560
by an essay which covered the story's importance and also discussed the period of science fiction

09:41.560 --> 09:45.200
history to which it belonged. Gunn explains how that volume led to others.

09:45.920 --> 09:51.880
By the time I got finished with the manuscript, I had felt that it really, unlike most books,

09:52.040 --> 09:55.900
came out even better than I thought it was going to, and I proposed that we go ahead

09:56.500 --> 10:04.040
with a second and third volume. They said, let's wait and see how this does, and eventually

10:04.040 --> 10:12.720
after it had done better than they thought, they agreed that I could go on to volume two

10:12.720 --> 10:25.120
and three, which covered the period from 1900 to approximately 1940, and then from 1940

10:25.120 --> 10:34.020
to 1970, or actually late 1976. Gunn has recently published a fourth volume in the

10:34.040 --> 10:37.540
science fiction series and says that it's now finished. The title for the entire series

10:37.540 --> 10:41.100
is the Road to Science Fiction, and it stands as a major work of science fiction criticism.

10:41.700 --> 10:44.240
We'll talk some more about it with James Gunn next time.

