12:17.820 --> 12:19.660
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon.

12:20.200 --> 12:23.980
James Gunn is noted not only as an author of science fiction, but as a critic of the

12:23.980 --> 12:26.380
field and as a chronicler in the story of its development.

12:26.680 --> 12:31.140
Gunn has recently completed the last volume in his four volume series, The Road to Science

12:31.140 --> 12:35.520
Fiction. In this unique work, he traces the development of science fiction from the very

12:35.520 --> 12:38.200
beginning of recorded literature until the present day.

12:38.540 --> 12:42.520
What's different and valuable about Gunn's approach in the road to science fiction is

12:42.520 --> 12:46.320
that he uses the actual literature itself, from tales belonging to the ancient world

12:46.320 --> 12:47.300
and modern short stories.

12:47.600 --> 12:51.840
But each literary selection is accompanied by an essay which discusses the work's importance

12:51.840 --> 12:54.760
and deals with the historical period to which it belongs.

12:55.260 --> 12:58.740
When using the volumes then, a reader not only is getting some good science fiction,

12:58.740 --> 13:02.600
but he's picking up an education relating to the definition and development of science

13:02.600 --> 13:02.960
fiction.

13:03.500 --> 13:08.320
Except for the last one, each volume is also organized around a particular thesis or point.

13:08.920 --> 13:12.340
The first one, for instance, develops the idea that before real science fiction could

13:12.340 --> 13:15.400
exist, mankind had to recognize the concept of change.

13:16.380 --> 13:23.040
It seems to me that the essential nature of science fiction is that it deals with change.

13:23.930 --> 13:30.860
In fact, in order for us to recognize a story or a novel as being science fiction, we have

13:30.860 --> 13:38.060
to identify that part of it which is different from here and now, our everyday world.

13:39.880 --> 13:46.840
And so it deals with how people would react in changed circumstances.

13:48.940 --> 13:56.740
So, up to approximately the time of the Indesta Revolution, the very concept of change itself

13:57.310 --> 14:00.780
was alien to human minds.

14:02.170 --> 14:11.520
It seems to me, looking back over the history of humanity, that mostly people saw change

14:11.520 --> 14:23.100
as being only the eternal circle of the seasons changing from spring to summer to fall to

14:23.100 --> 14:24.620
winter and back again.

14:25.420 --> 14:31.840
And it wasn't until the Indesta Revolution and, of course, the scientific perceptions

14:32.060 --> 14:41.360
that preceded it and accompanied it, which began to create change that people saw could

14:41.360 --> 14:47.780
be beneficial and in which they could, over which they might be able to exercise some

14:48.040 --> 14:48.400
control.

14:48.660 --> 14:57.540
That is, it was man-made change created by human desires and intelligence and it could

14:57.540 --> 15:01.800
be controlled by humanity's exercise of intelligence.

15:02.380 --> 15:10.600
And it seems to me that science fiction was the literary response to that recognition.

15:11.660 --> 15:15.760
The next two volumes develop other ideas that Dunn believes are essential to the development

15:15.760 --> 15:20.460
of science fiction, the notion, for instance, that mankind is a species rather than isolated

15:20.460 --> 15:22.040
tribes or nations or races.

15:22.300 --> 15:26.460
But the last volume is a bit different. This is because it deals with the most recent science

15:26.460 --> 15:29.800
fiction stories and it's more difficult to tell which ones will be important.

15:30.880 --> 15:36.960
In the more current story, this is much more difficult to determine. You can't really say

15:36.960 --> 15:44.240
what stories are important until much after they've been published and you can't certainly

15:44.240 --> 15:49.660
say which are typical until you decide what the period really stands for.

15:50.080 --> 15:56.400
So what I did in the fourth volume was to select stories that I thought dealt with the

15:58.720 --> 16:05.840
literary uses of science fiction. And so that, the volume is primarily concerned not with

16:05.840 --> 16:10.800
questions of generic importance but the question of literary uses.

16:11.780 --> 16:15.560
Gunn has performed a valuable service to the field with the four volumes in his The Road

16:15.560 --> 16:16.680
to Science Fiction series.

16:17.060 --> 16:21.160
By defining science fiction, by demonstrating what makes it different from other types of

16:21.160 --> 16:25.580
literature and by revealing its origins, he's made science fiction more understandable

16:26.020 --> 16:27.140
and more respectable.

