18:06.180 --> 18:10.480
In much of his science fiction, James Gunn examines the question of what makes man happy.

18:11.220 --> 18:15.620
He extrapolates a future which seems plausible from current social conditions and asks the

18:15.620 --> 18:17.600
standard science fiction question, what if?

18:17.960 --> 18:23.040
In his 1963 novel The Joymakers, he fills out the question by asking what if man discovered

18:23.040 --> 18:27.180
a drug that would make him perfectly happy, even though it would remove him from the real

18:27.180 --> 18:27.560
world.

18:27.560 --> 18:32.380
Gunn answers the question by saying that man would probably accept the opportunity, and

18:32.380 --> 18:34.700
then he shows what happened to man in society as a result.

18:36.240 --> 18:43.940
Ultimately, as it worked out in the novel, it turned out that the people who wanted happiness

18:45.900 --> 18:55.000
to get what they want, since what one can get in the external world is limited by the

18:55.000 --> 18:59.980
number of people, and the number of people who want this particular thing, ultimately

19:00.440 --> 19:08.440
they get what they want by being fed illusions that they get what they want. And ultimately

19:08.440 --> 19:17.980
everybody ends up floating in amniotic cells living on dreams of success and accomplishment

19:17.980 --> 19:25.160
fed by a machine, which I eventually worked out to be that you are happy when you don't

19:25.160 --> 19:32.660
want anything anymore. And it occurred to me that that is the same as death, and ultimately

19:32.660 --> 19:40.840
the equation for that is that happiness equals death, and that life is still wanting something.

19:41.760 --> 19:47.240
One of Gunn's more recent books, The Dreamers, also published in Paperback as The Mind Master,

19:47.240 --> 19:52.000
also presents a society in which man has presumably achieved perfect happiness.

19:52.620 --> 19:57.280
And he does so through chemical memory. Any possible experience can be felt by an individual

19:57.280 --> 20:01.840
if he is injected with the DNA or RNA of someone who has actually undergone that experience.

20:02.440 --> 20:17.080
It is a comment on the fact that dreaming itself is a non-survival characteristic. It may be

20:17.080 --> 20:22.420
satisfying, ultimately the most satisfying experience, but as perhaps I said in The

20:22.420 --> 20:30.440
Joymakers is perhaps repeated here in a different way, that ultimate satisfaction or dreaming

20:31.360 --> 20:43.580
is a death activity, and that survival demands something less than total satisfaction.

20:44.480 --> 20:49.580
Both The Joymakers and The Dreamers, along with many of Gunn's other books, consist of

20:49.580 --> 20:54.780
a series of related novellas, rather than being a straightforward novel. Gunn says that he

20:54.780 --> 20:58.760
started this practice years ago, not long after he began writing science fiction for

20:58.760 --> 21:03.280
a couple of reasons. It allowed him to be paid twice, since he could publish each novella

21:03.280 --> 21:07.300
separately in a magazine before putting it with other novellas to make up a whole novel.

21:08.180 --> 21:18.920
And as a consequence, I have since that time mostly written my novels in the form of publishable

21:18.920 --> 21:25.520
fragments or individual stories. And in a way I think it's worked rather well, because

21:25.520 --> 21:34.800
in The Joymakers I was able to use as a framework, as a subject matter, really an idea rather

21:34.800 --> 21:42.520
than a person or a group of people. And so this novel, which extended over about 200

21:42.520 --> 21:47.940
years, picked up several different people, but basically was about one thing, the science

21:47.940 --> 21:54.280
of happiness. And similarly, the immortals, which also continued for about 200 years,

21:54.460 --> 22:04.300
and the listeners, which took, have covered about 150 years. And all of these seemed to

22:04.300 --> 22:09.240
me to focus on an idea, which is what science fiction mostly does.

