23:51.140 --> 23:54.900
The science fiction of James Gunn is based on strong, clear ideas that are developed

23:54.900 --> 23:56.840
in stories with a good deal of action in them.

23:57.020 --> 24:02.380
One of his better known books, a 1962 novel entitled The Immortals, is based on a classic

24:02.380 --> 24:07.500
science fiction premise. What if immortality were possible? What would it do to society

24:07.500 --> 24:08.480
and to human nature?

24:08.900 --> 24:13.460
The novel focuses on Marshall Cartwright, who is immortal, and a search forum by Leroy

24:13.460 --> 24:17.440
Weaver, a dying millionaire who wants Cartwright's blood so that he himself can be immortal.

24:18.120 --> 24:20.320
But the novel is more than a chase or a search.

24:21.620 --> 24:28.000
Certainly, the notion of the search for the immortal, the person that I call Cartwright,

24:29.380 --> 24:37.020
Marshall Cartwright, was in there to provide a core of interest. But I was primarily interested

24:37.640 --> 24:46.620
in the novel on the impact of the possibility of immortality on society itself, and interested

24:46.620 --> 24:56.120
in dealing with those kinds of impulses that people have relating to immortality and longevity.

24:56.980 --> 25:01.860
By examining people's reactions to immortality, Gunn hopes to make a point about human nature.

25:02.440 --> 25:09.160
And in a certain sense, the immortals embodies as well as anything else that I've written,

25:10.020 --> 25:18.460
my basic philosophical position in my work that can be traced through almost all of it,

25:18.460 --> 25:27.700
I suspect, that there are no real villains in life. There are only people who want the

25:27.700 --> 25:34.740
same things everybody else wants, but who are willing to do to get them things that

25:34.740 --> 25:45.420
other people are not willing to do. And that the best things in life can be wanted too

25:45.420 --> 25:54.000
much, that if you anything that is considered good can be an evil. And I suppose one of

25:54.000 --> 26:01.960
the basic concepts with which I began the immortals was the concept that everybody thinks

26:01.960 --> 26:09.900
that it would be wonderful to live forever. But what if you had a man who accidentally

26:10.280 --> 26:16.760
could live forever, but who also whose blood could rejuvenate other people, and his life

26:16.760 --> 26:24.720
would be made miserable. And from there, of course, the entire extrapolation about the

26:24.720 --> 26:36.400
ways in which society, knowing the possibility of immortality, would force people, would force

26:36.400 --> 26:46.400
society to pour more and more and more money into medicine until the law of diminishing

26:46.400 --> 26:54.600
returns would mean that half of the world would be devoted to medicine and everybody

26:54.600 --> 27:05.560
else would be starving in the slums. Gun does indeed show the negative effects of

27:05.560 --> 27:10.480
the inequality, cause medical costs to rise drastically, and would also create a society

27:10.480 --> 27:14.480
so obsessed with seeking to live forever that it would forget to live for now.

27:15.060 --> 27:19.540
In 1969 there was a television series based on the immortals. We asked Gun what he thought

27:19.540 --> 27:19.820
of it.

27:20.660 --> 27:27.660
Well I thought it was a total disaster, and that's not uncommon of course, but the resemblances

27:28.400 --> 27:38.120
between the novel and the book are very slight. My book starts with the immortal being a drifter

27:38.120 --> 27:45.080
who comes in and sells a pint of blood, and then disappears for the rest of the novel

27:45.080 --> 27:53.960
until the very end. And the television series is all about the immortal and his being pursued,

27:53.960 --> 28:02.000
and eventually it turns into simply another search for the papers, another fugitive. Somebody

28:02.000 --> 28:05.520
is being chased, but it makes no real difference why he's being chased.

